ngth n. Kasai et al. [22] gave the first linear time algorithm for the computation of the LCP-array. Their algorithm uses
e string S , the suffix array, the inverse suffix array, and of course the LCP-array. Each of the arrays requires 4n bytes, thus
e algorithm needs 13n bytes in total (for an ASCII alphabet). The main advantage of their algorithm is that it is simple
d uses at most 2n character comparisons. But its poor locality behavior results in many cache misses, which is a severe
sadvantage on current computer architectures. Manzini [31] reduced the space occupancy of Kasai et al.â€™s algorithm to
bytes with a slow down of about 5%â€“10%. He also proposed an even more space-efficient (but slower) algorithm that
erwrites the suffix array. Recently, KÃ¤rkkÃ¤inen et al. [19] proposed another variant of Kasai et al.â€™s algorithm, which
mputes a permuted LCP-array (PLCP-array). In the PLCP-array, the lcp-values are in text order (position order) rather
an in suffix array order (lexicographic order). This algorithm is much faster than Kasai et al.â€™s algorithm because it has
much better locality behavior. However, in virtually all applications lcp-values are required to be in suffix array order, so
at in a final step the PLCP-array must be converted into the LCP-array. Although this final step suffers (again) from a
or locality behavior, the overall algorithm is still faster than Kasai et al.â€™s. SirÃ©n [43] showed that the PLCP-array can be
mputed directly from a compressed suffix array. In a different approach, Puglisi and Turpin [39] tried to avoid cache misses
using the difference cover method of KÃ¤rkkÃ¤inen and Sanders [21]. The worst-case time complexity of their algorithm is
(nv) and the space requirement is n+O(n/âˆšv+ v) bytes, where v is the size of the difference cover. Experiments showed
at the best run-time is achieved for v = 64, but their algorithm is still slower than Kasai et al.â€™s; see the experimental
sults in [19]. This is because it uses constant time range minimum queries, which take considerable time in practice. Just
cently, Gog and Ohlebusch [12] presented a very space efficient and fast LACA, which trades character comparisons for
che misses.
Wavelet tree
The wavelet tree introduced by Grossi et al. [13] supports one backward search step in O (logÏƒ) time. To explain this
ta structure, we may view the ordered alphabet Î£ as an array of size Ïƒ so that the characters appear in ascending
der in the array Î£[1..Ïƒ ], i.e., Î£[1] = $ < Î£[2] < Â· Â· Â· < Î£[Ïƒ ]. We say that an interval [l..r] is an alphabet interval if it is a
binterval of [1..Ïƒ ]. For an alphabet interval [l..r], the string BWT[l..r] is obtained from the Burrowsâ€“Wheeler transformed
ring BWT of S by deleting all characters in BWT that do not belong to the sub-alphabet Î£[l..r] of Î£[1..Ïƒ ]. As an example,
nsider the string BWT = nle_pl$nnlleee_eaae and the alphabet interval [1..4]. The string BWT[1..4] is obtained from
e_pl$nnlleee_eaae by deleting the characters l, n, and p. Thus, BWT[1..4] = e_$eee_eaae. The wavelet tree of
e string BWT over the alphabet Î£[1..Ïƒ ] is a balanced binary search tree defined as follows. Each node v of the tree
rresponds to a string BWT[l..r] , where [l..r] is an alphabet interval. The root of the tree corresponds to the string BWT =
T[1..Ïƒ ] . If l = r, then v has no children. Otherwise, v has two children: its left child corresponds to the string BWT[l..m]
d its right child corresponds to the string BWT[m+1..r] , where m =  l+r2 . In this case, v stores a bit vector B[l..r] whose
th entry is 0 if the i-th character in BWT[l..r] belongs to the sub-alphabet Î£[l..m] and 1 if it belongs to the sub-alphabet
[m + 1..r]. To put it differently, an entry in the bit vector is 0 if the corresponding character belongs to the left subtree
d 1 if it belongs to the right subtree; see Fig. 2. Moreover, each bit vector B in the tree is preprocessed so that the queries
nk0(B, i) and rank1(B, i) can be answered in constant time [17], where rankb(B, i) is the number of occurrences of bit b
B[1..i]. Obviously, the wavelet tree has height O (logÏƒ). Because in an actual implementation it suffices to store only the
t vectors, the wavelet tree requires only n logÏƒ bits of space plus o(n logÏƒ) bits for the data structures that support rank
eries in constant time.
Instead of reviewing the implementation of one backward search step on a wavelet tree, we present a generalization
