The function getIntervals takes O (logÏƒ) time for each interval, whereas the remaining statements of Algorithm 2 take
nstant time per interval. Thus, the run-time of Algorithm 2 is in O (n logÏƒ). 
Algorithm 2 uses only the wavelet tree of the BWT of S , a queue to store the Ï‰-intervals and the LCP-array. Because a
actical implementation should use as little space as possible, we next show how to reduce the space consumption of the
tter two. The second components (-values) of the queue entries need not be stored because one can simply count how
any Ï‰-intervals with |Ï‰| =  enter the queue; see Algorithm 3 for details. For a fixed , the Ï‰-intervals with |Ï‰| =  do
t overlap. Thus, they can be stored in two bit vectors, say B and E of size n, and an Ï‰-interval [i.. j] is stored by setting
e bits B[i] and E[ j] (due to singleton intervals, we actually need two bit vectors). By the invariant mentioned above, at
y point in time Algorithm 2 has to deal with at most two different -values. Therefore, we can replace the queue with
ur bit vectors of length n. The price to be paid for this is an increase in the worst-case time complexity. For each -value,
o bit vectors of length n are scanned to determine all Ï‰-intervals with |Ï‰| = . So the number of scans is proportional
the maximum lcp-value. Since this can be n âˆ’ 2 (consider the string S = anâˆ’1$), the time complexity rises to O (n2).
owever, in practice the maximum lcp-value is only a fraction of n [25], and on average it is O (logn) [7].)
For this reason, we prefer the following hybrid approach. For a fixed , if there are more than n2 logn Ï‰-intervals with
| =  (note that this can happen only O (logn) times), we use the bit vectors; otherwise we use the queue. More precisely,
e start with the queue, switch to the bit vectors when there are more than n2 logn Ï‰-intervals with the current -value,
d switch back if there are less than n2 logn Ï‰-intervals with the current -value. Note that the queue uses at most n bits
cause each queue entry is an interval that can be represented by two numbers using logn bits each. This hybrid approach
es not increase the worst-case time complexity as we show next. There are nlogn blocks of length logn in a bit vector of
