2. Shortest absent words
As a second application, we show that our approach allows us to compute shortest absent words. This is relevant because
ort DNA sequences that do not occur in a genome are interesting to biologists. For example, the fact that the human
nome does not contain all possible DNA sequences of length 11 may be due to negative selection. For this reason, several
gorithms have been developed that compute shortest absent words; see [5,15,16,37,45]. Our approach allows us to give
alternative algorithm for this task.
efinition 6.2. Given string S , a string Ï‰ âˆˆ (Î£ \ {$})+ is called an absent word if it is not a substring of S . The shortest absent
ords problem is to find all shortest absent words.
In the following, let Ïƒ be the size of Î£ \{$}. If Ïƒ = 1, say Î£ \{$} = {a}, then S consists solely of aâ€™s. That is, S = an , where
is the length of S . In this case, the shortest absent word is obviously an+1. Therefore, we may assume that Ïƒ > 1. We
fine a tree structure as follows. The root of the interval-tree is the Îµ-interval [1..n], and the children of an Ï‰-interval [i.. j]
e the cÏ‰-intervals returned by getIntervals([i.. j]), where c = $. Clearly, if the Ï‰-interval [i.. j] has less than Ïƒ children,
en every non-occurring child corresponds to an absent word. In other words, if for some c âˆˆ Î£ \ {$}, the cÏ‰-interval is
pty, then cÏ‰ is not a substring of S . Our algorithm can be viewed as a depth-first traversal through this (virtual) tree.
uring the traversal, the shortest absent words that have been detected so far are stored in a list, while a variable len stores
eir length. For each absent word Ï‰ with |Ï‰|  len, we proceed by case distinction. If |Ï‰| = len, then Ï‰ is added to the
t. Otherwise, if |Ï‰| < len, then len is set to |Ï‰| and the list is set to [Ï‰]. We next show that the initial value of len can be
per bounded without sacrificing correctness. Since there are at most nâˆ’ k substrings of length k in S , while there are Ïƒ k
ssible strings of length k, it follows that there must be an absent word of length k provided that Ïƒ k > nâˆ’k. In particular,
ere must be an absent word of length logÏƒ n. Therefore, if we initially set len to logÏƒ n, the algorithm will find all
ortest absent words. For how many substrings Ï‰ of S must the procedure getIntervals be applied? Clearly, it need not be
As pointed out by an anonymous reviewer, F [i] can also be obtained by a range quantile query on the wavelet tree; see [11].
